  "text": "The Rust trait obligation chain is implemented across several key components in the rustc compiler:\n\n## Core Data Structure: ObligationForest\nThe foundation is `ObligationForest` (compiler/rustc_data_structures/src/obligation_forest/mod.rs), a utility data structure that tracks outstanding trait obligations in a tree structure. It implements a forest of obligation trees where each node represents an obligation that must be satisfied. The `ForestObligation` trait defines the interface for obligations, and `ObligationProcessor` defines how obligations are processed during resolution.\n\n## Obligation Tracking: FulfillmentContext\n`FulfillmentContext` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs) is the primary trait engine that drives trait resolution. It uses `ObligationForest` internally to store pending predicates as `PendingPredicateObligation` objects. The context maintains a list of obligations that must be satisfied and tracks which are resolved, which have errors, and which remain pending.\n\n## Obligation Processing: FulfillProcessor\n`FulfillProcessor` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs) implements the `ObligationProcessor` trait and contains the logic to process individual obligations. It works with a `SelectionContext` to determine how obligations will be resolved. The processor returns `ProcessResult` values indicating whether an obligation is unchanged (ambiguous), changed (with sub-obligations), or has errored.\n\n## Candidate Assembly: SelectionContext\n`SelectionContext` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/mod.rs) performs the core trait selection. It maintains the obligation stack using `TraitObligationStack` to prevent infinite recursion. The selection process begins by examining in-scope impls, caller obligations, and builtin traits through `assemble_candidates` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/candidate_assembly.rs), which assembles a `SelectionCandidateSet` of possible implementations.\n\n## Impl Matching\nThe `match_impl` function (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/mod.rs:2502) unifies the obligation with impl trait headers. It normalizes trait references, instantiates fresh variables for impl generics, and uses unification to determine if an impl matches the obligation. The function returns normalized impl arguments on success.\n\n## Candidate Confirmation\nOnce a candidate is selected, `confirm_candidate` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/confirmation.rs) unifies output type parameters with those found in the obligation, yielding either an `ImplSource` on success or a `SelectionError`. This process handles various candidate types including user-defined impls (via `confirm_impl_candidate`), builtin impls, and parameter bounds.\n\n## Error Reporting\nFor unsatisfied trait bounds, `report_selection_error` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/fulfillment_errors.rs) generates diagnostic messages. The error reporting system provides detailed diagnostics including suggestions from compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/suggestions.rs and on_unimplemented notes from compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/on_unimplemented.rs.\n\n## New Trait Solver\nThe compiler also contains an alternative implementation for the new trait solver in compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/solve/fulfill.rs and compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/solve/select.rs, which uses a different architecture based on goal evaluation.\n\nThe entire chain flows as: ObligationForest registers predicates → FulfillmentContext processes through FulfillProcessor → SelectionContext assembles candidates → match_impl validates impl matching → confirm_candidate unifies types → Error reporting provides diagnostics for failures."
}

